SIMPLE: pillage
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pillage
<hw>Pil"lage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
<ets>piller</ets> to plunder. See <er>Pill</er> to plunder.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of pillaging; robbery.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is taken from another or others by open
force, particularly and chiefly from enemies in war; plunder; spoil;
booty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which <qex>pillage</qex> they with merry march bring home.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Plunder; rapine; spoil; depredation.</syn>
<usage> -- <er>Pillage</er>, <er>Plunder</er>. <xex>Pillage</xex> refers
particularly to the act of stripping the sufferers of their goods, while
<xex>plunder</xex> refers to the removal of the things thus taken; but
the words are freely interchanged.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pillage</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pillage
<hw>Pil"lage</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pillaged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pillaging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To strip of money
or goods by open violence; to plunder; to spoil; to lay waste; <as>as,
to <ex>pillage</ex> the camp of an enemy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mummius . . . took, <qex>pillaged</qex>, and burnt their city.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pillage</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pillage
<hw>Pil"lage</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take spoil; to plunder; to
ravage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were suffered to <qex>pillage</qex> wherever they went.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pillager</ent>⟦br⟧
